    "summary": "Efficient estimation of disease prevalence within populations is critical during epidemic outbreaks. This research addresses this challenge by developing a one-stage group testing strategy incorporating Bayesian methods and viral load information. Prevalence estimation from imperfect tests is challenging as observations are binary, with three unknown parameters: prevalence, specificity, and sensitivity. This creates a fundamental model identifiability problem where multiple parameter combinations can produce the same pool test results, making it impossible to determine the actual prevalence from the observed data. In such cases, the likelihood function does not point to a single best estimate but instead allows many possible solutions. Standard maximum likelihood methods, which rely on a w"
